Need to chose a car and a SUV from an American, Japanese, and German manufacturer. I am choosing the following vehicles:

American Car: Ford FusionSE

American SUV: Ford Explorer4WD

Japanese Car: Toyota CamrySE

Japanese SUV: Honda PilotEX-L

German Car: Volkswagen Jetta

German SUV: Mercedes GLK-ClassGLK350

#Get 100 samples for each vehicle
set.seed(419)
Ford_FusionSE = sample_n(subset(UsedCars, Model =="FusionSE"), 100)
Ford_Explorer4WD = sample_n(subset(UsedCars, Model =="Explorer4WD"), 100)
Toyota_CamrySE = sample_n(subset(UsedCars, Model =="CamrySE"), 100)
Honda_PilotEX_L = sample_n(subset(UsedCars, Model =="PilotEX-L"), 100)
Volkswagen_Jetta = sample_n(subset(UsedCars, Model =="Jetta"), 100)
Mercedes_GLK_ClassGLK350 = sample_n(subset(UsedCars, Model =="GLK-ClassGLK350"), 100)
Ford_FusionSE$Country = "USA"
Ford_FusionSE$VehicleType = "Car"

Ford_Explorer4WD$Country = "USA"
Ford_Explorer4WD$VehicleType = "SUV"

Toyota_CamrySE$Country = "JPN"
Toyota_CamrySE$VehicleType = "Car"

Honda_PilotEX_L$Country = "JPN"
Honda_PilotEX_L$VehicleType = "SUV"

Volkswagen_Jetta$Country = "GER"
Volkswagen_Jetta$VehicleType = "Car"

Mercedes_GLK_ClassGLK350$Country = "GER"
Mercedes_GLK_ClassGLK350$VehicleType = "SUV"
#Combine into one dataset
MyCars = rbind(Ford_FusionSE, Ford_Explorer4WD, Toyota_CamrySE, Honda_PilotEX_L, Volkswagen_Jetta, Mercedes_GLK_ClassGLK350)
head(MyCars)

Question 3

#Based on just what you see in the boxplots and summary statistics comment on whether you think there are significant differences in the mean prices among your six car models. Also comment on any concerns you see about the conditions for the ANOVA for means model

The means for all of the sedans are much lower than the means for the SUVs. Similarly the Standard Deviations for all the sedans are lower than their SUV counterparts. ANOVA models want to determine if we predict “significantly” better using seperate means and SDs (alternative hypothesis) rather than the overall mean and SD (null hypothesis).

Question 4

Null Hypothesis: Overall mean price is the best predictor in our model

Alternative Hypothesis: Seperate mean prices for each model predict better than the overall mean.

#Construct an ANOVA model for the mean price by car model. Include the output showing the ANOVA table; state hypotheses and provide a conclusion in the context of your data

Single_Car_Mod = aov(Price~factor(Model),data=MyCars)
summary(Single_Car_Mod)
##                Df    Sum Sq   Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)    
## factor(Model)   5 2.204e+10 4.407e+09   120.8 <2e-16 ***
## Residuals     594 2.166e+10 3.647e+07                   
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

In the above model we see that the only predictor (factor(Model)) is significant with a p-value of effectively 0 (p < 2e-16). This mean that Model (a categorical predictor) is significant and we can reject the Null Hypothesis that the overall mean price of all the vehicles in the dataset is the best way to predict a new vehicle’s price.

Question 5

#Produce plots and/or summary statistics and comment on the appropriateness of the following conditions for your data: normality of the residuals, and equality of the variances

plot(Single_Car_Mod)

The data appears to have zero mean looking at the Residuals vs Fitted plot. Also there appears to be constant variance of the residuals around this horizontal reference line. The QQ plot shows a decently close to normal distribution until we look at the bottom tail of the plot. This deviation from the 45 degree reference line may indicate that these values are not quite normally distributed.

Two-Way ANOVA

Question 7

Null Hypothesis 1: The vehicle’s country of origin does not change the expected mean price of the vehicle

Alternative Hypothesis 2: The vehicle’s country of origin affects the expected mean price of the vehicle

Null Hypothesis 2: The vehicle type will change the expected mean price of the vehicle

Alternative Hypothesis 2: The vehicle type will change the expected mean price of the vehicle

#Construct an ANOVA model for the mean price using the country of the company and the type of vehicle as predictors (without an interaction). Include the output showing the ANOVA table; state hypotheses and provide a conclusion in the context of your data. If your ANOVA model indicates there are significant differences among the car price means: Discuss where the significant differences occur using Tukey HSD methods

Multi_Car_Mod = aov(Price~factor(Country)+factor(VehicleType), data=MyCars)
summary(Multi_Car_Mod)
##                      Df    Sum Sq   Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)    
## factor(Country)       2 1.854e+08 9.270e+07   2.452  0.087 .  
## factor(VehicleType)   1 2.098e+10 2.098e+10 555.045 <2e-16 ***
## Residuals           596 2.253e+10 3.780e+07                   
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Based on the model above, it appears that only VehicleType is a significant predictor in the model (p<2e-16). Based on this we cannot reject the first null hypothesis but we can reject the second null hypothesis. This means that we cannot conclude that the vehicle’s country of origin affects the price of a car but we can conclude that the vehicle type (car or SUV) does affect the price of the vehicle.

TukeyHSD(Multi_Car_Mod)
##   Tukey multiple comparisons of means
##     95% family-wise confidence level
## 
## Fit: aov(formula = Price ~ factor(Country) + factor(VehicleType), data = MyCars)
## 
## $`factor(Country)`
##             diff        lwr      upr     p adj
## JPN-GER  997.750  -446.9024 2442.402 0.2368049
## USA-GER 1301.255  -143.3974 2745.907 0.0873826
## USA-JPN  303.505 -1141.1474 1748.157 0.8743821
## 
## $`factor(VehicleType)`
##             diff      lwr      upr p adj
## SUV-Car 11827.46 10841.51 12813.42     0

Using TukeyHSD() we see that the only significant pairwise comparison is the one looking at VehicleType (SUV-Car). This further supports the model saying that only VehicleType is a significant predictor of a vehicle’s price.

Question 8

#Produce plots and/or summary statistics to comment on the appropriateness of the following conditions for your data: normality of the residuals, and equality of the variances

plot(Multi_Car_Mod)

The data appears to have zero mean looking at the Residuals vs Fitted plot. Also there appears to be constant variance of the residuals around this horizontal reference line. The QQ plot shows a decently close to normal distribution until we look at the bottom tail of the plot. This deviation from the 45 degree reference line may indicate that these values are not quite normally distributed. The normality and constant variance of this model are similar to the normality and constant variance seen in the Single_Car_Mod from the One-Way ANOVA part of the assignment.

Question 9

Null Hypothesis 1: There is no difference in the mean price across the Country predictor

Alternative Hypothesis 1: At least one Country has a significantly different mean price

Null Hypothesis 2: There is no difference in the mean price across the VehicleType predictor

Alternative Hypothesis 2: At least one Vehicle Type has a significantly different mean price

Null Hypothesis 3: There is no difference in the mean price across the interaction of the Country and VehicleType predictors

Alternative Hypothesis 3: At least one of the interactions of Country and Vehicle Type has a significantly different mean price

#Construct an ANOVA model for the mean price using the country of the company and the type of vehicle as predictors with the interaction. Include the output showing the ANOVA table; state hypotheses and provide a conclusion in the context of your data. If your ANOVA indicates there are significant differences among the car price means: Discuss where the significant differences occur using Tukey HSD methods

Interaction_Car_Mod = aov(Price~factor(Country)+factor(VehicleType)+factor(Country)*factor(VehicleType), data=MyCars)
summary(Interaction_Car_Mod)

The ANOVA test tells us that both the VehicleType predictor and the interaction of the Country and VehicleType predictors were both significant with p-values of 2e-16(i.e. 0) and 8.63e-06 respectively. Looking at the TukeyHSD pariwise tests the following interactions were significant:

JPN:Car-GER:Car

GER:SUV-GER:Car

JPN:SUV-GER:Car

USA:SUV-GER:Car

GER:SUV-JPN:Car

JPN:SUV-JPN:Car

USA:SUV-JPN:Car

GER:SUV-USA:Car

JPN:SUV-USA:Car

USA:SUV-USA:Car

USA:SUV-JPN:SUV

As we can see from the above comparisons, most of the significant differences come from comparing SUVs to cars across the vehicle’s country of origin. This further indicates that the better predictor of a vehicle’s price is it’s Vehicle Type and not the Country the vehicle was made in.

Question 11

#Recall that we can also handle a categorical predictor with multiple categories (like your six car models) using ordinary multiple regression if we create indicator variables for each category and include all but one of the indicators in the model. Run an ordinary multiple regression to predict Price using the Model variable. Since Model has text values, R will automatically create the required indicator variables (i.e. treat it as a factor) and leave one out when fitting the model. Interpret each of the coefficients in the “dummy” regression by what they mean in the context of prices (or mean prices) of the different car models

Linear_Car_Mod = lm(Price~factor(Model), data=MyCars)

Question 12

#One possible drawback of the analysis for this assignment is that different people might have chosen cars with quite different ages (or mileages) when collecting their samples. Thus an apparent “difference” between two car models might be due to one sample having considerably more older cars in it than another. Construct a model that allows you to check for price differences between your car models after accounting for variability that might be due to the mileage of the cars. Explain how you use the output from the model to address this question

#Use Mileage variable as a predictor

Multi_Linear_Car_Mod = lm(Price~factor(Model)+Mileage, data = MyCars)
summary(Multi_Linear_Car_Mod)
